## Navigation

The `proj` and `wt` fish functions installed by devbox-setup operate here:

- `proj ls` — list every project under this root
- `proj <name>` — cd into a project (new-style → `<name>/base/`)
- `proj new <name>` — scaffold a new project with `git init` + hooks
- `proj clone <url>` — clone a remote into a new project
- `proj convert <name>` — migrate an old-style project to the `base/` layout

For worktrees on new-style projects:

- `wt add <branch>` — create a worktree at `<project>/<branch>/`
- `wt fork <branch>` — fork a worktree from current HEAD
- `wt ls` / `wt status` — list worktrees (status shows PR state)
- `wt rm [-f] <name>` — remove worktree and branch (slash branches accepted)
- `wt clean [--age <days>]` — remove merged + stale worktrees (.wtkeep skips)

`proj` (no args) prints the full help.

## Project layouts

Two layouts coexist here:

- **New-style**: `<project>/{CLAUDE.md, .claude/, base/, <worktree>/, ...}`. The repo
  lives in `base/`; `CLAUDE.md` and `.claude/` at the wrapper level are inherited
  into every worktree as symlinks.
- **Old-style**: `<project>/.git/` at the wrapper itself. Single working tree, no
  worktree workflow. `proj convert <name>` migrates to new-style.

Not every subdirectory has to follow these — ad-hoc clones, archives, and
non-`proj` directories live here too. The tooling will warn but never modify.

